{{Infobox language |name=North Levantine Arabic |nativename={{lang|ar|اللهجة الشامي الشمال}} |states=[[Lebanon]], [[Syria]], [[Chukurova]] ([[Turkey]]) |speakers= 24.2 million |date=2014-2015 |ref=<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/apc|title=Arabic, North Levantine Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Semitic languages|Semitic]] |fam3=[[Central Semitic languages|Central Semitic]] |fam4=[[Arabic]] |fam5=[[Levantine Arabic]] |dia1=[[Lebanese Arabic]] |dia2=[[Languages of Syria#Arabic|Syrian Arabic]] |dia3=[[Çukurova|Çukurovan Arabic]] |script=[[Arabic alphabet]] |lc1=apc |notice=IPA |glotto= nort3139 |glottorefname=North Levantine Arabic |map=Levantine Arabic Map.jpg |mapcaption= {{legend|#fff000|[[Lebanese Arabic|North Levantine]]}} }}
'''North Levantine Arabic''' ({{lang-ar|اللهجة الشامي الشمال}}) is a subdivision of [[Levantine Arabic]], a [[variety of Arabic]]. It stems from the north in [[Turkey]], specifically in the coastal regions of the [[Adana Province|Adana]], [[Hatay Province|Hatay]], and [[Mersin Province|Mersin]] provinces,<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/apc|title=Arabic, North Levantine Spoken|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/map/TR|title=Turkey|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref> to [[Lebanon]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://glottolog.org/resource/languoid/id/nort3139|title=Glottolog 3.2 - North Levantine Arabic|last=|first=|date=|website=glottolog.org|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-07-16}}</ref><ref name=":0" /> passing through the Mediterranean coastal regions of [[Syria]] (the [[Latakia Governorate|Latakia]] and [[Tartus Governorate|Tartus]] governorates) as well as the areas surrounding [[Aleppo]] and [[Damascus]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/map/JOSY|title=Jordan and Syria|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-07-16|language=en}}</ref> It is also known as '''Syro-Lebanese Arabic''',<ref name=":0" /> though that term is sometimes used to mean all of Levantine Arabic.<ref name="Versteegh 2009">{{Cite book |url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/401165899 |title=Encyclopedia of Arabic language and linguistics |last=Versteegh |first=Kees |date=2009 |publisher=Brill |isbn=9789004177024 |location=Leiden |pages=170 |oclc=401165899}}</ref>
With over 24 million native speakers worldwide as of 2015,<ref name=":0" /> Northern Levantine Arabic is used for daily speech mainly in Lebanon and Syria, while most of the written and official documents and media use [[Modern Standard Arabic]]. Its dialect continuum has been described as one of the two "''dominant (prestigeful) dialect centres of gravity for Spoken Arabic''".<ref>{{cite book|title=Handbook of the International Phonetic Association: A Guide to the Use of the International Phonetic Alphabet|last1=Decker|first1=Donald M.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1999|isbn=9780521637510|location=Cambridge, United Kingdom|page=|pages=51}}</ref>
== Dialects == * '''[[Languages of Syria#Arabic|Syria]]''': The [[Damascus Arabic|dialect of Damascus]] and the dialect of Aleppo are well-known.<ref name=":0" /> * '''[[Lebanese Arabic|Lebanon]]''': North Lebanese, South Lebanese (Metuali, Shii), North-Central Lebanese (Mount Lebanon Arabic), South-Central Lebanese (Druze Arabic), Standard Lebanese, Beqaa, Sunni Beiruti, Saida Sunni, Iqlim-Al-Kharrub Sunni, Jdaideh<ref name=":0" /> * '''[[Çukurova]], [[Turkey]]''': Cilician/Çukurovan<ref name=":0" />
== Literature == The [[Trinitarian Bible Society]] has published portions of the Bible in North Levantine Arabic: in 1939 they published the Gospel of Luke, in 1973 they published the Gospel of Matthew, and in 1981 they published the Book of Genesis<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.language-archives.org/item/oai:rosettaproject.org:rosettaproject_apc_gen-1|title=The Book of Genesis in Lebanese|website=www.language-archives.org|others=The Long Now Foundation|access-date=2018-11-20}}</ref> and the First Letter to the Corinthians. These were all in Arabic script.
